Stephen makes his way through Belize and Guatemala. Belize is the only country
in Central America that used to be a British colony and it has English as its
official language and the Queen is still head of state. He pays a visit to the
Wildtracks Animal Rescue Centre in Belize City where he finds out how to
bottle-feed an injured baby manatee before meeting up with the last vestiges of
the British Army. He then makes his way to Turneffe where he talks to a latter
day Robinson Crusoe called Alan. Stephen later makes his way into Guatemala
which has a very indigenous culture. He takes part in a sacred Mayan ritual
with shaman Tata Gilberto and his acolyte Ricky Lopez, in the temples of Tikal.
The then travels by bus into the mountains of the Ixil. <div align='right'> <hr

Stephen starts his journey on the Sante Bridge separating El Paso in Texas from
Ciudad Juarez in Mexico. Ge travels on a converted school bus to avoid
attracting the attention of the locals and heads towards Chihuahua. Along the
way he sees some of the local cowboys before he experiences the enduring
patriotism of a local hero, the revolutionary Pancho Villa. He then gets on
board the El Chepe train as he makes his way into the Sierra Madre mountains
and the Copper Canyon.
